The fungal colonies that have been growing on PDA (four weeks) were used for genomic DNA extraction. Liquid nitrogen was used to grind the mycelium into a fine powder, and the manufacturer’s instructions were followed to extract the DNA using the DNA extraction kit (E.Z.N. AFungal DNA Mini Kit, D 3390-02, Omega Bio-Tek). The DNA products were stored for a long time at -20 ° C and retained at 4 ° C for DNA amplification. DNA was amplified by Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR) for two genes, the large subunit (28 S , LSU ) and internal transcribed spacers (ITS1- 5.8S-ITS2). The LSU gene was amplified using the primers LROR (5’-TCCTGAGGGAAACTTCG-3’) and LR5 (5’- ACCCGCTGAACTTAAGC-3’) ( Vilgalys and Hester, 1990 , Rehner and Samuels, 1994) and nuclear ITS was amplified using the primers ITS5 (5’-GGAAGTAAAAGTCGTAACAAGG-3’) and ITS4 (5’-TCCTCCGCTTATTGATATGC- 3’) (
White et al . 1990
). Sterilized water (9.5 µl), 2×Power Taq PCR MasterMix (Bioteke Co., China ) (12.5 µl), each forward and reverse primers (1 μl) and DNA template (1 μl) were used for amplification reactions.

The combined data set of LSUs and ITS sequences contained 2001 characters, of which 809 characters are constant, 899 characters are parsimony-informative, while 293 variable characters are parsimony-uninformative in the maximum parsimony ( MP ) analysis (TL = 5235, CI = 0.436, RI = 0.571, RC = 0.249, HI = 0.564). The RAxML analysis of the combined dataset yielded a best-scoring tree (
) with a final ML optimization likelihood value of - 23613.540071. The matrix had 1362 distinct alignment patterns, with 38.76% of undetermined characters or gaps. Estimated base frequencies; A = 0.259082, C = 0.223873, G = 0.296879, T = 0.220166; substitution rates AC = 0.996332, AG = 1.803468, AT = 1.641793, CG = 0.949204, CT = 3.840249, GT = 1.000; proportion of invariable sites I = 0.243698; gamma distribution shape parameter α = 0.701633. The Bayesian analysis resulted in 10000 trees after 1,000,000 generations. All analyses ( ML , MP and BYPP ) gave similar results and were in agreement with previous studies based on multi-gene analyses (
Qiao et al . 2021
,
Zheng et al . 2022
).

Combined gene phylogeny showed considerably high bootstrap support within clades (
). Bootstrap support values for ML , MP (≥70%) and BYPP (≥0.95) are given above each branch respectively (
). Paramicrothyrium bambusae isolates( MFLU 19-2729and NCYU 19-0085) clustered with the type of Paramicrothyrium ( P . chinensis ) isolates ( IFRDCC 2258 and IA 20) with strong statistical support (100% ML , 99% MP , 1.00 BYPP ). In addition, Paramicrothyrium bambusae isolates grouped with 100% ML , 99% MP , and 1.00 BYPP support. Tumidispora thailandica isolates ( MFLU 19-2771 and NCYU 19-0090) grouped with the type of Tumidispora ( T . shoreae ) isolates ( MFLUCC 12-0409 and MFLUCC 14-0574) with high bootstrap support (100% ML , 100% MP , 1.00 BYPP ,
) and grouped with each other with 100% ML , 99% MP , 1.00 BYPP support (
).

