In this study, Paramicrothyrium bambusae provided a well-supported lineage with P . chinensis (
). As well as, both have similar morphological characteristics, such as superficial, scattered, flattened, circular, dark brown to black thyriothecia and with an irregular ostioles, without a darkened ring (
Wu et al . 2011
). However, other morphological characteristics could not be compared as they have different morphs. Paramicrothyrium bambusae can be distinguished from the type by phylogenetic evidence and their smaller thyriothecia (90–120 × 100–130 μm vs 420–590 μm diam.) (
Wu et al . 2011
). Apart from P . bambusae , another new species, Tumidispora thailandica is also introduced here with support from both morphology and molecular data. Our phylogeny shows that T . thailandica clustered with type ( T . shoreae ) with high statistical support (
). Both have similar morphological characteristics, such as flattened, circular, brown to black thyriothecia with a prominent darkened area around the central ostiole, cylindrical to cylindric-clavate, short pedicellate asci and 1-septate, hyaline ascospores with a swollen apical cell (
Ariyawansa et al . 2015
). Nevertheless, T . thailandica can be distinguished from the type by distinct size differences of asci and ascospores. In addition, T . thailandica has fusiform, rounded ends ascospores with two appendages in the upper cell, whereas T . shoreae has narrowly fusiform ascospores with sub-papillate ends and lacking of appendages (
Ariyawansa et al . 2015
). However, for the expansion of these two genera, additional collections are necessary for future studies.

Swofford, D.L. ( 2002 ) PAUP : phylogenetic analysis using parsimony, Version 4 . 0 b10 . Sinauer Associates, Sunderland MA . Available from: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3348772 (accessed
15 th August 2022
).
